Abbreviations¶

COCO - common objects in context

CNN - convolutional neural network

DETR - detection transformer

GIoU - generalised intersection over union

RBC - red blood cell

RDT - rapid diagnostic test

Introduction¶

Malaria¶

Malaria is an infectious disease that is transmitted through the bites of female Anopheles mosquitoes infected with the parasite Plasmodium. Despite being a treatable disease, nearly 400,000 people died of malaria in the year 2020. 94% of these deaths occured in Sub-Saharan Africa, where cases often go undetected due to the lack of testing facilities. According to the World Health Organisation, testing is crucial to the control of malaria as it allows the incidence of the disease to be studied on a national and regional level. This information is needed to direct resources to where they are needed most, assess the impact of existing programmes and plan effective responses to future outbreaks.

Diagnosis¶

Currently, the gold standard for malaria diagnosis is microscopic examination of patient's blood samples. In addition to detecting the presence of Plasmodium infected red blood cells, a skilled laboratorian can also identify the stage of infection and the species of Plasmodium, which are key factors in determining the course of treatment. However, the presence of artefacts in blood smears as well as variations in cellular morphology can make diagnosis extremely challenging. Furthermore, rural hospitals in Sub-Saharan Africa, where malaria is most prevalent, often lack the trained professionals required to perform these tests.

Malaria can also be tested for by using a rapid diagnostic test (RDT), which is simpler to use. However, these tests are expensive, have variable sensitivity and, unlike microscopic examination, cannot distinguish between different species of Plasmodium or quantify the number of infected cells. Although RDTs are useful in diagnosing and monitoring malaria, especially in rural areas that lack specialist laboratories, RDT's do not eliminate the need for microscopic examination.

(Plasmodium falciparum mortality rate per 100,000 people across Africa and South Asia in 2019.)

Aim¶

Motivation¶

Currently, regions that do not have the facilities to perform microscopic examination must instead rely on RDTs, which are expensive and often inaccurate. Automating the detection and classification of infected cells from microscopy images will widen the availability of fast and reliable malaria testing, especially in rural and impoverished areas. Wider testing will enable better surveillance of malaria cases and, consequently, more effective control of the disease. In addition, this model could be adapted to diagnose a wide range of fungal and parasitic diseases that are traditionally diagnosed by microscopic examination such as sleeping sickness, lymphatic filariasis and babesiosis.

Dataset¶

The aim of this study was to automate the labour intensive process of microscopic examination for the diagnosis of malaria. For this task, we used dataset BBBC041v1 from the Broad Bioimage Benchmark Collection (BBBC), which contains images of blood smears taken from individuals infected with Plasmodium vivax. The images were manually annotated with bounding boxes and class labels for each cell. Uninfected red blood cells and leukocytes were labelled as such whilst infected red blood cells (RBCs) were labelled according to the parasite's stage of development; gametocyte, ring, trophozoite or schizont.

Methodology¶

Previously, a two step approach has been used to detect and classify infected cells in the BBBC041v1 dataset. First, a Faster Region-based Convolutional Neural Network (Faster R-CNN) was used detect individual cells and distinguish uninfected RBCs from infected cells. Infected cells were further classified into gametocytes, rings, trophozoites and schizonts using a conventional CNN such as Alex-Net. In this study, I adopt a similar approach and fine-tune a pre-trained Detection Tansformer (DETR) model to detect cells and a custom CNN to classify them.

DETR is a model, released by Facebook AI research in 2020, that repurposes the transformer encoder decoder architecture to solve an object detection task. Transformers were originally designed to solve natural language processing tasks but, as DETR has demonstrated, they are also uniquely suited to object detection tasks. This is because the encoder of the transformer uses an attention mechanism that is able to learn long-range dependencies between different regions of images, which is useful since bounding boxes span many pixels in an image.

Another reason for using DETR is that, compared to current state-of-the-art object-detection models, DETR uses a much simple architecture. It has fewer hyperparameters and does not require a-priori information about objects, such as anchors or aspect ratios, to be inputted prior to training. This makes it much simpler to fine-tune DETR on a custom dataset compared to other pre-trained models.

Create COCO annotation file¶

In order to convert the class label and bounding box information in the json files into the format that DETR requires, I used the DetrFeatureExtractor module from the Transformers library. Since this module takes in a COCO-style annotation file, the annotations in the json files were first converted to the COCO format.

In [43]:
def COCOann(dataset, path, encoder):
    '''
    This function uses the information in a Pandas DataFrame to create a COCO-style annotation file with three
    sections; CATEGORIES, IMAGES and ANNOTATIONS. 
    '''
    bbox = np.empty((dataset.shape[0], 6))
    paths = []
    labels = []
    
    # Iterate through dataframe and extract bounding box and class label information
    for i, row in dataset.iterrows():
        x_min = row['objects']['bounding_box']['minimum']['c']
        y_min = row['objects']['bounding_box']['minimum']['r']
        x_max = row['objects']['bounding_box']['maximum']['c']
        y_max = row['objects']['bounding_box']['maximum']['r']
        width = x_max - x_min
        height = y_max - y_min
        image_width = row['image']['shape']['c']
        image_height = row['image']['shape']['r']
        coordinates = [x_min,y_min,width,height,image_width, image_height]
        bbox[i] = coordinates 
        paths.append(row['image']['pathname'])
        labels.append(row['objects']['category'])

    for i, column in enumerate(['x_min', 'y_min', 'width', 'height', 'image_width', 'image_height']):
        dataset[column] = bbox[:,i]

    dataset['pathname'] = paths
    dataset['category'] = labels
    category_dict = {'red blood cell':1, 'trophozoite':2, 'schizont' :2, 'difficult':2, 'ring':2,
       'leukocyte':2, 'gametocyte':2}
    dataset['category_id'] = dataset['category'].map(category_dict)

    dataset = dataset.drop(['image','objects'], axis=1)
    dataset.columns = ['ann_id', 'image_id', 'x_min', 'y_min', 'width', 'height', 'image_width', 'image_height',
                        'pathname', 'category','category_id']

    # CATEGORIES section - maps class IDs to name of cell. Only two categories RBC and other.
    CATEGORIES = [
    {   'id': 1,
        'name': 'red blood cell',
        'supercategory': 'RBC',
    },
    {   'id': 2,
        'name': 'other',
        'supercategory': 'notRBC',
    },]

    # IMAGES section of COCO annotation file - contains image ID and file path to image.
    IMAGES = []

    for index, row in enumerate(dataset['pathname'].unique()):
        my_dict = {'height':1200, 'width':1600}
        my_dict['id'] = dataset[dataset['pathname'] == row].iloc[0]['image_id']
        my_dict['file_name'] = row[8:]
        IMAGES.append(my_dict)

    # ANNOTATIONS section of COCO annotation file - contains bounding box and class label for each cell in image.
    ANNOTATIONS = []

    for index, row in dataset.iterrows():
        my_dict = {}
        my_dict['area'] = row['width']*row['height']
        my_dict['bbox'] = [row['x_min'], row['y_min'], row['width'], row['height']]
        my_dict['image_id'] = row['image_id']
        my_dict['category_id'] = row['category_id']
        my_dict['id'] = row['ann_id']
        ANNOTATIONS.append(my_dict)

    data_coco = {}
    data_coco['images'] = IMAGES
    data_coco['categories'] = CATEGORIES
    data_coco['annotations'] = ANNOTATIONS
    # Save COCO annotation file in same directory as notebook.
    json.dump(data_coco, open(path, "w"), indent=4, cls=encoder)

    return 

class NpEncoder(json.JSONEncoder):
    def default(self, obj):
        if isinstance(obj, np.integer):
            return int(obj)
        if isinstance(obj, np.floating):
            return float(obj)
        if isinstance(obj, np.ndarray):
            return obj.tolist()
        return super(NpEncoder, self).default(obj)

Create PyTorch dataset¶

Here, I defined a PyTorch Dataset class which inherits from Torchvision's CocoDetection and has a custom __getitem__ method that reads in the images in a COCO annotation file and their corresponding target information (i.e. class labels and bounding boxes for each cell in the image). It then uses the DetrFeatureExtractor to convert the target information into the format DETR takes.

In [3]:
class CocoDataset(torchvision.datasets.CocoDetection):
    ''' Args:
    root(string): directory where images are stored.
    annFile(string): Path to COCO annotation file.
    feature_extractor(callable): function that transforms image.
    '''
    def __init__(self, root, annFile, feature_extractor):
        super().__init__(root, annFile)
        self.feature_extractor = feature_extractor
        
    def __getitem__(self, idx):
        '''
        Read in and transform image from annotation file and return tensor of image and bounding box and class labels.
        '''
        img, target = super().__getitem__(idx)      
        image_id = self.ids[idx]
        target = {'image_id': image_id, 'annotations': target}
        encoding = self.feature_extractor(images=img, annotations=target, return_tensors="pt") 
        pixel_values = encoding["pixel_values"].squeeze() # remove batch dimension
        target = encoding["labels"][0] # remove batch dimension
        return pixel_values, target

Having created training and validation datasets, I then used a PyTorch DataLoader to divide each dataset into batches of 32 images to facilitate batch training of the DETR model.

In [5]:
def collate_fn(batch):
    '''
    DataLoader uses this function to process the tuple returned by the __getitem__ method of the CocoDataset class.
    '''
    pixel_values = [item[0] for item in batch]
    labels = [item[1] for item in batch]
    batch = {}
    batch['pixel_values'] = pixel_values
    batch['labels'] = labels
    return batch

train_dataloader = DataLoader(train_dataset, collate_fn=collate_fn, batch_size=16, shuffle =True)
val_dataloader = DataLoader(val_dataset, collate_fn=collate_fn, batch_size=16)

Customising pre-trained DETR model¶

Model description¶

DETR uses a traditional CNN to collect image features; these features are flattened and inputted into an encoder-decoder transformer, which predicts bounding boxes and class labels. The encoder uses an attention mechanism to learn long range dependencies between different parts of an image, which the decoder uses to simultaneously output a fixed number of predictions. DETR then performs bipartite matching, using the Hungarian algorithm, to match predictions with their corresponding ground truths. Once a matching is found that minimises the matching cost, the loss on the bounding boxes is calculated using a mixture of 'L1' and 'Generalised Intersection over Union' (GIoU) whilst the loss on the class labels is calculated using cross-entropy loss.

Importing pre-trained model¶

The original DETR model was trained on the COCO image dataset, which contains 92 different classes. Using a similar approach as !PAPER!, I modified the model to predict only two classes (red_blood_cell and not_red_blood_cell). Since DETR predicts a fixed number of objects per image, I increased the num_queries parameter from 100 to 250 to accomodate for the larger number of objects (in this case cells) present in each image in this dataset.

class DETRModel(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self,num_classes,num_queries):
        super().__init__()
        self.num_classes = num_classes  
        self.num_queries = num_queries
        # Load pre-trained DETR model
        self.model = torch.hub.load('facebookresearch/detr', 'detr_resnet50', pretrained=True)
        self.in_features = self.model.class_embed.in_features 
        # Modify classification head to predict only two classes of cells and 250 bounding boxes per image
        self.model.class_embed = nn.Linear(in_features=self.in_features,out_features=self.num_classes)
        self.model.num_queries = self.num_queries
        
    def forward(self,images):
        return self.model(images)

Training and evaluation functions¶

In [56]:
def train_fn(dataloader,model,epoch):
    model.train()
    # SetCriterion computes the loss of DETR 
    criterion.train()
        
    for i, batch in enumerate(tqdm(dataloader)):
        pixel_values = torch.stack(batch['pixel_values'])
        labels = [{k: v.to(device) for k, v in t.items()} for t in batch['labels']]
        for lab in labels:
            lab['labels'] = lab.pop('class_labels')
        
        # Return pred_logits (size = [batch_size, 100, 8]) and pred_boxes
        pred = model(pixel_values)  
        loss_dict = criterion(pred, labels)
        weight_dict = criterion.weight_dict
        losses = sum(loss_dict[k] * weight_dict[k] for k in loss_dict.keys() if k in weight_dict)
        
        # Tensorboard log
        x = i + (epoch*69)
        writer.add_scalar(f"Train/Average", losses, x)
        writer.add_scalar(f"Train/class_error", loss_dict['loss_ce'], x)
        writer.add_scalar(f"Train/bbox", loss_dict['loss_bbox'], x)
        writer.add_scalar(f"Train/GIOU", loss_dict['loss_giou'], x)
        writer.add_scalar(f"Train/cardinality", loss_dict['cardinality_error'], x)
        
        # Backpropagation
        optimizer.zero_grad()
        losses.backward()
        optimizer.step()
    return 

def eval_fn(dataloader, model,epoch):
    model.eval()
    with torch.no_grad():
        for i, batch in enumerate(tqdm(dataloader)):
            pixel_values = torch.stack(batch['pixel_values'])
            labels = [{k: v.to(device) for k, v in t.items()} for t in batch['labels']]
            for lab in labels:
                lab['labels'] = lab.pop('class_labels')
            
            pred = model(pixel_values)
            loss_dict = criterion(pred, labels)
            weight_dict = criterion.weight_dict
            losses = sum(loss_dict[k] * weight_dict[k] for k in loss_dict.keys() if k in weight_dict)
            
            # Tensorboard log
            x = i + (epoch*69)
            writer.add_scalar(f"Val/Average", losses, x)
            writer.add_scalar(f"Val/class_error", loss_dict['loss_ce'], x)
            writer.add_scalar(f"Val/bbox", loss_dict['loss_bbox'], x)
            writer.add_scalar(f"Val/GIOU", loss_dict['loss_giou'], x)
            writer.add_scalar(f"Val/cardinality", loss_dict['cardinality_error'], x)
    return

def eval_test(dataloader, model):
    '''
    Determine the average loss, cross entropy loss, L1 loss and GIoU for each epoch and return the average of 
    all these losses over eight epochs.
    ''' 
    model.eval()
    test_loss = {'Avg.':0, 'CEL':0, 'L1':0, 'GIoU':0}
    
    with torch.no_grad():
        for i, batch in enumerate(tqdm(dataloader)):
            pixel_values = torch.stack(batch['pixel_values'])
            labels = [{k: v.to(device) for k, v in t.items()} for t in batch['labels']]
            for lab in labels:
                lab['labels'] = lab.pop('class_labels')

            pred = model(pixel_values)
            loss_dict = criterion(pred, labels)
            weight_dict = criterion.weight_dict
            losses = sum(loss_dict[k] * weight_dict[k] for k in loss_dict.keys() if k in weight_dict)
            
            test_loss['Avg.'] += losses
            test_loss['CEL'] += loss_dict['loss_ce']
            test_loss['L1'] += loss_dict['loss_bbox']
            test_loss['GIoU'] += loss_dict['loss_giou']
            
        for i, k in test_loss.items():
            test_loss[i] /=8
    return test_loss

Out[31]:
{'Avg.': 0.6718, 'CEL': 0.4085, 'L1': 0.0267, 'GIoU': 0.2367}

After training for two epoches, the L1 norm, which describes the loss for the coordinates of the corners of the bounding box, is very low. The GIoU, which is a type of scale-invariant loss that measures the degree of overlap between the predicted and ground truth is quite low. This suggests that the model can predict boxes that are in the vicinity of the ground truth boxs but with poor overlap. This was expected as, during training, the L1 norm rapidly decreased whereas the GIoU did not significantly improve. This is discussed further in the next section.

For the class labels, the cross entropy loss is high, suggesting that the model is unable to distinguish uninfected red blood cells from other types of cells. This was also expected as the differences between the cell types are extremely subtle.

Out[48]:
<matplotlib.legend.Legend at 0x7fcb78f91490>

Whilst the model is able to detect most cells with good overlap (high GIoU), it struggles to detect cells in regions of the image where many cells are crowded together. In addition, for some cells, the model predicts multiple bounding boxes and, in the image on the left, it predicts a large bounding box that encompasses several cells. Together, this may explain, even though most cells are detected with high overlap, why the model has a low GIoU score. In addition, it must be noted that the ground truth bounding boxes were manually drawn and in many cases, the bounding boxes exclude edges of cells, miss cells near the borders of the image, encapsulate more than one cell or include too much of the background. Taking this into consideration, the error in the predicted bounding boxes for the majority of the cells may be considered acceptable.

Most importantly, due to limited computational resources, the model was only trained for two epochs on a relatively small dataset of 1000 images and training was stopped before the average training loss had converged. Training for a greater number of epochs until convergence would greatly improve the ability of the model to accurately detect between cells and distinguish between red blood cells and other cell types.

Conclusion¶

In this study, I successfully fine-tuned a pre-trained DETR model, which uses a novel transformer architecture, to detect individual cells in a microscopy image of a blood smear. The model is able to detect most cells in a given image with very good overlap between the ground truth and predicted bounding boxes. Optimisation of this model will yield more accurate bounding boxes, especially in crowded regions, and better distinction between RBCs and other types of cells. In the second part of this notebook, I use a convolutional neural network (CNN) to perform more fine-grained classification and, subsequently, combine the fine-tuned DETR model with the CNN to completely automate the task of malaria diagnosis by microscopic examination.
